    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Blog', item: 'https://bighornthreads.com/blog/' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: post.title, item: `https://bighornthreads.com/blog/${post.slug}/` },
   ],
  },
  {
   '@type': 'FAQPage',
   mainEntity: [
    {
     '@type': 'Question',
     name: 'What PPE is required on a construction site under OSHA rules?',
     acceptedAnswer: {
      '@type': 'Answer',
      text: 'OSHA 29 CFR 1926 Subpart E sets the baseline: hard hats meeting ANSI Z89.1, eye and face protection meeting ANSI Z87.1, hearing protection where exposure exceeds 85 dB time-weighted average, foot protection meeting ASTM F2413, and high-visibility apparel meeting ANSI/ISEA 107 for any worker exposed to vehicle traffic. Trade-specific additions include NFPA 70E flame-resistant clothing for electrical work near energized parts, and NFPA 2112 for oil and gas work with flash-fire exposure.',
     },
    },
    {
     '@type': 'Question',
     name: 'Can company logos be embroidered or printed on PPE without voiding the rating?',
     acceptedAnswer: {
      '@type': 'Answer',
      text: 'Yes, but with strict rules. On hi-vis (ANSI/ISEA 107), decoration must not reduce minimum required background fabric or retroreflective tape coverage and must follow the manufacturer\'s decoration guidelines. On FR clothing (NFPA 70E and 2112), decoration thread must be aramid (Nomex) — standard polyester thread melts in arc events and voids the rating. Heat transfer and screen-print inks must be FR-rated as well; standard plastisol on FR fabric voids certification.',
     },
    },
    {
     '@type': 'Question',
     name: 'Does Nevada have additional PPE rules beyond federal OSHA?',
     acceptedAnswer: {
      '@type': 'Answer',
      text: 'Yes. Nevada is a state-plan state operating under Nevada OSHA, which adopts federal standards plus state-specific additions. The most consequential for Las Vegas construction is the Nevada heat illness prevention rule effective 2026, which requires written heat illness prevention plans, mandatory rest in shade, water access, and acclimatization protocols when the heat index reaches specified thresholds. Mesh-back hi-vis and moisture-wicking FR options have become operationally necessary, not just preferred.',
     },
    },
    {
     '@type': 'Question',
     name: 'What hi-vis class is required for road and utility work?',
     acceptedAnswer: {
      '@type': 'Answer',
      text: 'ANSI/ISEA 107 Class 2 is the minimum for daytime workers exposed to traffic under 50 mph. Class 3 is required for highway work over 50 mph, night-shift utility work, and any work where a flagger or worker needs to be visible at greater distances. Class E is for pants only and pairs with a Class 2 or Class 3 top to create a "Class 3 ensemble." On large data center and industrial construction sites, prime contractors increasingly spec Class 3 site-wide regardless of speed limits because of concurrent crane operations and material delivery traffic.',
     },
    },
    {
     '@type': 'Question',
     name: 'What CAT rating do FR shirts need for electrical work?',
     acceptedAnswer: {
      '@type': 'Answer',
      text: 'NFPA 70E specifies arc-rated clothing by hazard category. CAT 1 (minimum 4 cal/cm²) covers most general electrical work. CAT 2 (minimum 8 cal/cm²) is the most common spec for commercial and industrial electricians working on 480V systems and switchgear. CAT 3 (25 cal/cm²) and CAT 4 (40 cal/cm²) are required for higher-energy substation, transformer, and utility work. The hazard analysis of the specific task drives the spec — a journeyman wiring a panel needs different protection than a tech doing live switchgear maintenance.',
     },
    },
